// Churn corpus (ARC leak net) — EVENT-LOOP REGISTRY ownership (timers).
//
// Guards the 71ede9d fix that made the loop registries counted owners:
// timer registration retains the tick-pusher closure, and cancel / one-shot
// completion release it (before the fix, the loop dispatched freed closures
// — the http.ext/sockets.ext failures). Each iteration registers a timer
// whose subscription owns a fresh heap Payload, then cancels it in the same
// iteration: the registry's release at cancel, plus the buffer-handler
// release when the Timer drops at scope exit, are all that stand between
// those captures and a leak. A missing release leaks N closures (+ their
// Payloads); a release without the registration retain is the old
// freed-closure dispatch (crash / oracle divergence). One 0ms one-shot after
// the loop exercises the fire-then-self-release completion path with a
// constant count, so the program terminates. Never more than one live
// registration (capacity is 64). Only `sink` survives, so the root set is
// CONSTANT in N.
//
// SHAPE MATTERS: the callback is bound BEFORE the Timer is declared. Lambdas
// capture ALL visible locals by snapshot, so a callback written after the
// Timer exists would capture it and close the cycle
// Timer -> buf -> handler -> Timer — a true rc-cycle (§15's asterisk) that
// neither engine reclaims and that would red-herring this guard.
// @N@ is substituted by fuzz/churn_leak.py.
class Payload { public int v = 0; }
void run(int n) {
    int sink = 0;
    for (int i in 1..n) {
        Payload p = Payload();
        p.v = i;
        var cb = (k) => console.writeln(p.v);   // captures p; Timer not visible yet
        Timer t = std::every(0);
        t.subscribe(cb);              // handler owns p through cb; no cycle
        t.cancel();                    // registry must release its retain
        sink = sink + p.v;
    }                                  // t drops -> buf drops -> handler + p drop
    console.writeln(sink);
    Payload last = Payload();          // constant-count fire path
    last.v = 424242;
    var fireCb = (k) => console.writeln(last.v);
    Timer once = std::after(0);
    once.subscribe(fireCb);            // fires once, then self-releases
}
run(@N@);
